 <section id="battery-chemistry" class="mb-16">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">2. Which Battery Chemistry Is Better for Power Banks?</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">Know your battery types to pick between cost and performance. Both <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lithium-ion_battery" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">Li-ion</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lithium_polymer_battery" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">Li-polymer</a> batteries power modern power banks. Each has its own traits.</p>
 
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Lithium-Ion (Li-ion)</h3>
 <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-2">
 <li><strong>Energy Density:</strong> 150-250 Wh/kg</li>
 <li><strong>Cost:</strong> Lower manufacturing cost</li>
 <li><strong>Shape:</strong> Cylindrical or prismatic cells</li>
 <li><strong>Lifespan:</strong> 500-1,000 charge cycles</li>
 <li><strong>Weight:</strong> Heavier per capacity unit</li>
 </ul>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mt-4">Best for: Budget-conscious buyers seeking high capacity at lower prices. <a href="/about" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">Learn about our manufacturing process</a>.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Lithium-Polymer (Li-Po)</h3>
 <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-2">
 <li><strong>Energy Density:</strong> 100-180 Wh/kg</li>
 <li><strong>Cost:</strong> Higher manufacturing cost</li>
 <li><strong>Shape:</strong> Flexible, custom form factors</li>
 <li><strong>Lifespan:</strong> 300-500 charge cycles</li>
 <li><strong>Weight:</strong> Lighter, ultra-thin designs</li>
 </ul>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mt-4">Best for: Slim power banks, premium devices, and applications requiring custom shapes — including <a href="/products/power-bank/heating-battery" class="text-brandOrange font-bold underline">heated apparel batteries</a> (7.4V / 12V) where custom connector and voltage tuning matter more than raw mAh.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 
 <div class="bg-brandBlue/5 border border-brandBlue/20 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3">Industry Data Point</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">According to <a href="https://www.batterydiscipline.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">Battery University</a>, lithium batteries experience approximately 20-30% capacity degradation after 500 full charge cycles. This means a 10,000mAh power bank may only deliver 7,000-8,000mAh after 18 months of regular use.</p>
 </div>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4 mt-4">According to BloombergNEF, semi-solid-state batteries offer 30% higher energy density than conventional Li-polymer cells while eliminating thermal runaway risk. This technology is rapidly entering the power bank market, with leading manufacturers beginning volume production. For a detailed overview, read our <a href="/blog/semi-solid-state-power-bank-oem" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">semi-solid-state power bank OEM guide</a>.</p>

 <div class="bg-brandBlue/5 border-l-4 border-brandOrange p-5 rounded-r-xl mb-6"><p class="text-[11px] font-black text-brandOrange uppercase tracking-widest mb-1">QUICK ANSWER</p><p class="text-slate-700 text-sm"><strong>Which battery type is best for power banks?</strong> Li-polymer batteries offer slim profiles ideal for everyday carry, while semi-solid-state batteries provide 30% higher energy density and zero fire risk. For budget-conscious buyers, standard Li-ion cells offer the lowest cost per mAh. WOWOHCOOL offers all three options depending on your brand positioning and target market.</p></div>
 </section>

 <section id="pd-standards" class="mb-16">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">3. What Charging Protocols Power Modern Power Banks?</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">Modern power banks use standard charging protocols. Know <strong>USB-C PD 3.1, PPS, and 140W laptop charging</strong> to avoid buying gear that won't work together.</p>
 
 <p class="text-sm text-slate-500 mb-6">Learn more: <a href="/blog/usb-c-pd-fast-charging-guide" class="text-brandBlue underline">USB-C PD Fast Charging Guide &rarr;</a></p>
 
 <div class="space-y-6">
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 uppercase mb-3">USB-C Power Delivery (PD) 3.1</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3"><a href="https://www.usb.org/usb-pd" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">USB Power Delivery</a> is the universal standard developed by the USB-IF organization. It supports power profiles from 15W to 240W across different voltage levels (5V, 9V, 15V, 20V, 28V).</p>
 <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-3">
 <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-brandBlue/10 text-brandBlue text-xs">PD 3.1 = Up to 240W</span>
 <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-brandBlue/10 text-brandBlue text-xs">PPS = Programmable Power Supply</span>
 <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-brandBlue/10 text-brandBlue text-xs">140W = MacBook Pro Charging</span>
 </div>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mt-4">Key advantage: Bi-directional charging allows using the power bank as both a charger and a device being charged through the same USB-C port.</p>
 </div>

 <div class="bg-white border border-brandOrange/30 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h3 class="font-black text-brandOrange uppercase mb-3">PD 3.1 EPR (Extended Power Range)</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3"><strong>EPR</strong> is what unlocks the full 240W ceiling of PD 3.1. It adds three high-voltage rails — <strong>28V, 36V, 48V</strong> — on top of the standard 5/9/15/20V already in PD 3.0. Without EPR, even a "PD 3.1" power bank is functionally capped at 100W.</p>
 <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-2 mb-3">
 <li><strong>28V rail:</strong> Up to 140W. Covers MacBook Pro 16, ThinkPad X1 Extreme.</li>
 <li><strong>36V rail:</strong> Up to 180W. Covers Dell XPS 17, Razer Blade 15 base models.</li>
 <li><strong>48V rail:</strong> Up to 240W. Covers Razer Blade 16, ROG Strix, mobile workstations.</li>
 </ul>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Both ends matter: the power bank, the cable (5A E-Marker rated), and the device must all support EPR for the high-voltage handshake to succeed. WOWOHCOOL ships 240W EPR-ready in the <a href="/products/power-bank/laptop-power" class="text-brandBlue font-bold underline">laptop power bank line</a> with full 28V/36V/48V negotiation support.</p>
 </div>

 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 uppercase mb-3">Quick Charge (QC) by Qualcomm</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm mb-3"><a href="https://www.qualcomm.com/quick-charge" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandOrange hover:underline">Quick Charge</a> technology, developed by Qualcomm, uses variable voltage (5V, 9V, 12V, 20V) to optimize charging speeds. The latest QC 5.0 delivers 100W+ charging with 70% improved efficiency over QC 4.0.</p>
 <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mt-3">
 <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-brandOrange/10 text-brandOrange text-xs">QC 5.0 = 100W+ output</span>
 <span class="px-2 py-1 bg-brandOrange/10 text-brandOrange text-xs">QC 4.0+ = USB PD compatibility</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h3 class="font-black text-slate-900 uppercase mb-3">Other Notable Standards</h3>
 <ul class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-3">
 <li><strong>Samsung AFC:</strong> Adaptive Fast Charging, proprietary to Samsung devices</li>
 <li><strong>Apple 20W PD:</strong> Apple's implementation of USB Power Delivery</li>
 <li><strong>VOOC/Warp Charge:</strong> OPPO/OnePlus proprietary fast charging (requires compatible cables)</li>
 <li><strong>PowerIQ:</strong> Anker's proprietary technology for device-optimized charging</li>
 </ul>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>

